i don't think that getz's problem was 'not knowing geography'. 
he re-arranged and re-made a traditional regional song for a worldwide jazz audience , so he just chose a title more fitting for an international public (Dear Old Stockholm: easy, fashionable, containing a well-known and well-visited placename) instead of a swedish tongue-twister like "Vaermlandsvisan". just my two cents, tho'.
Very good...
such an amazing track.....

Think it was Stan Getz who first made a jazz version of this. Anyway, he didn't know much about swedish geography: In sweden this song is called "Värmlandsvisan" and is an official song of the state Värmland, while Stockholm (the capital) is in a way different part of the country.

But it's still a wonderful melody and it's great he turned the world on to it (if it was Getz who reinterpreted it.)
This is not the version on 'Round Midnight ... Don't you hear the Brass Section?
